There are two TCP ports open on the target machine. There is a HTTP application on port 80, and RDP on port 3389. The target machine is running IIS HTTPD 10.0 on port 80, so I will start enumeration here.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


Doing a directory search showed /retro is available. Browsing to /retro displays the webpage above. Right away, I notice a username called wade. The target is running WordPress 5.2.1 for this /retro.


After enumerating for some time, I found the entry above. Is the string parzival a password?


And bingo! Using the password wade:parzival at http://10.10.92.43/retro/wp-admin/ I gained access to the WordPress application! Will this credential work against the port 3389?

Exploitation


And using xfreerdp with the credential wade:parzival, I gained access to the application on port 3389. Now I have a foothold on the target machine using RDP.

Privilege Escalation


I found this Github repository for PE vector. The image above contains the PoC to obtain a NT Authority on the target machine.


And following the instructions from the Github repository, I gained full NT Authority access on the target machine. I used the binary hhupd for the executable file.

Flags
